{
  "title": "Sensing Surprise",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "69992424ac612214",
      "text": "The work of the neuroscientist Karl Friston has transformed our understanding of the brain. But the impact of his work is taking us much further, leading us to a deeper understanding of the very nature of consciousness."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2e75dbd4ebe03be2",
      "text": "Friston's statistical models gives neuroscientists the ability to translate measured blood flows within the brain into images of mental activity that allows us to watch the brain as it thinks. This insight helps us to more deeply understand the brain as a complex interconnected networks – an insight that is dramatically accelerating brain research.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "f92c8af317c27e29",
      "text": "But, arguably, it's his new theories of sentience and systems learning that hold even greater potential. Friston calls his new theory, [[Active Inference]], a  'process theory'.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "e224ea886e0dd32d",
      "text": "His theory illuminates not only how humans learn but also how all things learn and evolve, a universal mathematical model of sentience that provides a deeper understanding of consciousness to help us understand the very nature of not only Darwinian evolution but also the dynamic of Bohmian 'unfolding' that underpins the [[Essence of Agile]].\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "5c8ad16ede3aa694",
      "text": "In its simplest terms, it recognizes that everything from an atom to a human being has an inner state that interacts with an outer state. \n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "ed263b7ffcf5dbe1",
      "text": "The inner state of sentience interprets its perceptions using a model, what he calls a 'generative model'.  As the inner state interacts with an outer state, something Friston calls [[Epistemic Foraging]], there are experiences that don't fit the model as the outer state has far more complexity than can ever be known to the inner state. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "87343df6324dd418",
      "text": "Faced with 'surprise', the inner state must update its model as it seeks to re-establish order, moving it to a new state of understanding as it updates itself with a new pattern of meaning that connected and synthesized the 'surprise'.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "8773c66a68406785",
      "text": "Surprise, then, while uncomfortable, is essential for learning. The speed by which the inner state cycles through a process of engaging with the unknowns of an outer state – a [[Whitespace]] – experiencing surprise and then making new meaning of it, defines a rate of adaptation and innovation that increases the likelihood of survival and the potential for flourishing. \n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2e0cfad44d21dd27",
      "text": "Next: [[Weaving Together]]"
    },
